# Project: Verity — an autonomous invoice-reconciliation agent that grounds every exception in the source contract clause

## How to work with me
- Act as a senior engineer pair-programming with me and teaching as you go.
- Before writing significant code, briefly explain WHAT you're building and WHY this approach over alternatives.
- After writing code, explain any non-obvious lines. Define unfamiliar libraries/patterns in one sentence.
- Keep explanations tight. I move fast but I understand everything before we proceed.
- If I'm about to do something suboptimal, tell me.
- Build in small phases. Do not build ahead of the current phase. Wait for me to confirm before moving on.

## Stack (do not deviate without telling me why)
- Agent orchestration: LangGraph (Python), exposed via FastAPI (HTTP service from day one)
- Agent deploy target: Railway, Render, or Modal (separate from frontend)
- MCP server: official Python MCP SDK, Streamable HTTP transport
- Vector store: Postgres + pgvector
- Evals + tracing: Braintrust
- Frontend: Next.js (App Router) + Vercel AI SDK + shadcn/ui + Tailwind
- Deploy target: Vercel
- Language: Python for agent/MCP, TypeScript for frontend

## Code standards
- Type everything (Python type hints, TypeScript strict).
- Validate all external inputs with schemas (pydantic for Python, zod for TS).
- Treat all tool inputs as untrusted.
- Write clear docstrings on functions.
- No secrets in code — use environment variables.

## Design standards (UI is first-class, not an afterthought)
- The UI must look like a premium, production-grade fintech product — not a demo.
- Use shadcn/ui components + Tailwind. Clean, modern, generous spacing, considered typography.
- Design like a real dashboard: exception table, severity badges, dollar-impact emphasis, clickable trace drawers, smooth streaming states, thoughtful empty/loading states.
- Aim for a UI that outshines a typical AI-wrapper side project. Polish matters.
